##How to keep a plague out of the first line of Defense

Perhaps the most important lesson of America's 200-plus-year experience in fighting infectious diseases is to learn to use "bad news" to correct problems and turn them into habits and institutions

Jin Yan | Wen
Mark | editor

Jin Yan | Wen

Mark | editor

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Many passengers wear face masks on a flight to California on January 29,2020. Figure / Fachen

On Feb. 7, the luxury cruise ship diamond princess reported 41 more confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia following the death of Wuhan Doctor Li Wenliang in the early hours of the morning, it was soon known as the "Plague Cruise" , "wandering in the ghost ship. ".

The honeymoon couple, Torres and Tyler Torres, were supposed to return to Irving, Texas, on this day, but were stuck in their cabins, bored, confused and anxious in isolation. "I spent two and a half years in graduate school learning how to help an infected or disabled person find a meaningful career in life, " Ms. Torres later quipped. "after getting my license, I realized that my first real patients were myself and my husband. "

Or honeymooning in quarantine or vacationing in a hospital until death do us part... an international public health crisis defines the world in the early 2020s.

World Health Organization Director General Tan Desai reported that as of 6:00 a.m. Geneva time on February 28, China had reported 78,959 cases of novel coronary pneumonia and 2,791 deaths to WHO. Outside China, 49 countries have reported 4,351 cases and 67 deaths. He announced that the same day the new global risk level of pneumonia epidemic from "high" to "very high.

As of the end of February, 60 people in the United States, where the Torres lived, had been diagnosed with new pneumonia. The Seattle area of Washington reported a new death from pneumonia on March 1, the second death in the state and the United States.

The virus has led to a reassessment of the responsiveness of countries'administrative and health systems. A minute's delay means more infections, more deaths, and greater social costs. Feng Daxuan, a former vice president of the University of Texas at Dallas who hosted a transatlantic teleconference between U.S. officials and the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention during SARS, told Caijing that the virus is the most democratic, it treats everyone the same.

Corrado Clini, a former Italian environment minister, told Caijing that the SARS outbreak should have led to a global, permanent, World Health Organization-backed research programme to combat the virus, but it did not; There is also no effective global surveillance and control system for infectious diseases, and the new crown pneumonia epidemic has caught everyone off guard. Perhaps the dramatic COVID-19 will reverse the trend of "de-globalisation" and economic decoupling.

Robert Hendler, a Texas Hospital Association clinical professor of Chief Medical Officer and University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center and former Parkland Hospital associate dean and chief quality officer, told CAIJING, "change is hard, but never squander a good crisis. If circumstances permit, we should learn quickly, not suppress the right action. "

When it comes to politics,

There are all kinds of uncertainties in the epidemic. To deal with the crisis of epidemic situation requires not only strong medical system and delicate medical network, but also careful political judgment and strategies. How Medicine and politics interact is fraught with trivialities and obstacles, but what emerges is a thrilling drama.

The Torres boarded the diamond princess, joined by some 3,700 passengers and crew from more than 50 countries and regions, and joined the ship as a showcase for a floating epidemic disaster in Port of Yokohama.

The Japanese government initially decided to contain the outbreak entirely outside its borders, with the result that neither the isolation at sea of the diamond princess nor the testing of potential contacts made much sense afterwards, it simply overwhelmed the health care system. As it turned out, the Japanese government's delays, coupled with its hasty and ineffective containment measures during the two weeks of isolation, were tactically and tactically passive.

"Diamond Princess" cruise the worsening of the epidemic, resulting in the United States, a series of domestic political games, and finally prompted the U. S. government to make the decision to evacuate overseas Chinese.

The Torres, along with 326 other Americans, boarded the 747 cargo plane. On a rainy night they got off the cruise ship, boarded a bus, stopped at the port for more than two hours before taking off, and arrived in Tokyo International Airport where the long wait began again.

The Torres were the end of a system that included the White House, federal agencies, Congress and parts of the military at the top. The COVID-19 was established on January 29, under the leadership of the Secretary of Health and Human Services (HHS) , Alex Azar, and coordinated through the National Security Council. Members include 12 high-level officials from health, Foreign Affairs, Homeland Security, transportation and other departments, as well as White House aides and medical experts, including the president's assistant for National Security, Redfield; the director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Institute of Medical Science Fossey; and Deputy Secretary of State Biegen.

As if that weren't enough, Donald Trump, who chaired the meeting on Jan. 29, tasked the task force with leading U.S. government agencies in responding to the COVID-19 outbreak and keeping him informed. In less than a month, the Donald Trump administration has taken a number of steps to deal with the outbreak, including declaring a public health emergency, imposing travel restrictions and mandatory quarantines.

Still, pressure is mounting on the Donald Trump administration. Anne Schuchat, deputy director of the CDC, said Feb. 25 that the United States hopes to build a large-scale response to prevent community transmission in the United States. Two days later, Donald Trump named vice president Michel Pensée to lead the U.S. efforts to prevent the new pneumonia, coordinating medical and other professionals to prevent the virus from spreading in the United States.

The White House has spent a good deal of time pondering whether to appoint such a head of state -- a man with a central role to better co ordinate the various stages of its operation. Michel Pensée became the head of the fight against the epidemic because of his experience in health policy during his time at the List of Governors of Indiana.

The various parts of this huge machine are in operation, in parallel work also in coordination and interaction. There is cooperation in the system, and there is always conflict and friction.

As the Torres couple disembarked, it began to rain in Yokohama, and from the sky came a notification of the Japanese test results: 14 of the 328 passengers who returned to the United States tested positive for the virus. So all bets were off. The original plan was to send passengers back to the United States only if they had been screened and showed no signs of illness. What do we do with these 14? The ball was kicked back to Washington.

Washington is still enjoying its Sunday afternoon. News of the 14 men came from the other side of the world, and the government officials in charge of the operation were in a tangle. According to media reports, the State Department and a senior health official in the Donald Trump administration are sticking to the plan, hHS Assistant Secretary and New Coronavirus Task Force member Robert Kadlec, who has similar functions to the Chinese Health Commission, said, "staff are prepared to deal with passengers who may develop symptoms on long-haul flights. The Boeing 747 will each have 18 quarantines and an infectious disease doctor will accompany them. "

Recalling the incident, a State Department spokesman told Caijing that the department has no higher priority than the well-being and safety of U.S. citizens overseas. The State Department follows HHS's assessment of the "high risk of new coronavirus infection" among passengers and crew of the diamond princess.

U.S. CDC officials did not agree with the 14 people chosen for fear of an infection on the plane, and Annie Schuhart, the CDC's chief deputy director, called the State Department specifically to voice objections and concerns. Unlike the Chinese CDC, which is part of the Health Commission, Feng Daxuan, who put forward the slogan "the Internet travels at the speed of light to fight SARS that travels at near-sonic speed, " told Caijing that the U.S. CDC can communicate directly with the president, has The authority to act immediately in the event of an outbreak, and the state operates according to its mode of command.

But in the 14-person arrangement, the State Department won, and the 14 passengers flew back on the same plane, isolated by the CBCS container biological control system. The U.S. CDC instead requested that the press release and its contents be removed, and the CDC-related content removed from the press release.

The challenge of this episode, which runs through this public health emergency, is that a game with the virus can be lost without precedent. Hendler told Caijing that American hospitals and medical workers have built an unbreakable culture of safety by fighting the disease, which has become a bulwark against the worst. Ideally, government agencies and departments should operate similarly, but in reality this is not always the case.

When the Torres returned to the United States, they found that the administration's response to the new coronavirus crisis had become a political issue, and that Congressional Democrats were not endorsing the Donald Trump administration's handling of the epidemic as it grew worse, described the Donald Trump administration's response as "slow and weak" .

Of the U.S. CDC

Since February 2020, the global spread of NCP has been accelerating to six continents.

February 26, the fall of Latin America, the same day the U.S. CDC suspected that a California patient tested positive for the virus, but it has not been exposed to any people infected with the virus, has not been to the outbreak of the country. That, the CDC said, could mean the first case of community-based transmission in the United States.

The U.S. CDC says it carries a lot of weight internationally. The world's top risk consulting firm, and Hong Kong's political and Economic Risk Consultancy (Perc) , have reported twice in 2003 and 2012 on the ability of countries around the world to cope with major and communicable diseases, the United States has twice topped the world in its ability to deal with public health emergencies.

On March 30,2009, a child in California developed flu symptoms and recovered a week later. After receiving medical institutions found unable to determine the type of virus, immediately reported to the California Department of Public Health, and on April 13 notified the United States CDC, 14 sent samples of the virus, the CDC confirmed that day is a new influenza virus. Another patient in California was seen on March 28, and the CDC notified California public authorities on April 17, immediately after receiving the sample. The CDC subsequently traced the source of infection in both cases, but found no history of exposure in livestock and suspected human-to-human transmission of the virus.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
N95 masks are sold out at a supermarket in California February 4,2020. FIGURE / method new

This terrible virus is the highly contagious H1N1"swine flu" . The mortality rate from swine flu was relatively low in 2009, at an estimated 0.02 per cent, but its pandemic caused about 285,000 deaths.

Aware of the seriousness of the problem, the U.S. CDC reported the case to the World Health Organization on April 18,2009, and on April 21, four days after receiving the second case, the CDC held a press conference to inform the public of the outbreak and initiate vaccine development, it also requires California to report all unclassifiable flu viruses; on April 22, the CDC launched an Emergency Response Center for the H1N1 outbreak; and on April 23, the CDC received two additional H1N1 cases from Texas. On the same day, the CDC completed the sequence of the virus sent from Mexico, confirmed that the H1N1 virus.

For non-professionals, this timeline is more one-way. A more intuitive reading of the efficiency of the U.S. CDC's decision making system would compare the data above to those in the middle of the response to the epidemic in countries with confirmed cases: from the first case to the reported CDC, it took three weeks for new pneumonia, and two weeks for H1N1; The National Health Service received 23 days for new pneumonia and 9 days for H1N1, and 291 cases for new pneumonia and only 4 cases for H1N1 when outbreak control was initiated. Although the 2020 figure compares with the 2009 figure, the U.S. CDC was more efficient a decade ago.

Allen Goroll, a tenured professor of general practice at Harvard Medical School and Massachusetts General Hospital, who is known for his pioneering work in primary care medicine, told Caijing: We basically know the lessons, is the importance of early reporting of outbreaks and a comprehensive public health response.

Before H1N1, there were outbreaks of everything from Yellow Fever, the infectious disease that broke out in 1793, as recently as 2012, Mers, Ebola outbreak... lessons from history drive the U.S. to continually adapt and reshape its decision making and Response Systems. Shao Xinli, chief executive officer of Delta International Health Services Group, told CAIJING that the infectious disease reporting system in the United States mainly relies on the self-supervision and management of state health departments, with the CDC taking the overall responsibility, state-level health departments and CDC no affiliation, more open and transparent decision-making, timely report to the CDC, the federal government will be in the epidemic prevention and control of resources and support. Government departments and epidemic prevention and control departments have their own responsibilities, diversified leadership, no conflict of interest, and will not conceal the epidemic.

A web-based platform launched in 2009 by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) , which allows health authorities at all levels to enter information about disease outbreaks. According to Shao, The United States now has a relatively complete disease information System, namely The National Outbreak Reporting System (NORS) . It supports state, local and regional public health agency partners in outbreak reporting. CDC NORS collects reports of outbreaks of intestinal disease caused by bacteria, viruses, parasites, chemicals, toxins, and unknown pathogens, as well as food-and water-borne outbreaks of non-intestinal disease. The appearance of NORS makes the system of intelligence monitoring and reporting more perfect, and avoids the artificial factors in the reporting mechanism.

When the United States conducts an outbreak survey, it is usually initiated by state, regional, and local public health agencies and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. These agencies collect information such as the date and location of the outbreak through NORS reports, about the number of people who are sick, their symptoms, and the pathogen that caused the outbreak.

At the end of February, the U.S. CDC took a more somber tone, saying that a new outbreak of pneumonia could occur in the United States at any time. The CDC has a strict reporting policy for major and new or unknown pandemics. Respiratory Disease are highly infectious, but pathogens are difficult to identify, and there is a dedicated "respiratory disease outbreak of unknown origin" (Urdo) working group.

Outbreaks of unknown causes, serious diseases requiring hospitalization or resulting in death, diseases that may require vaccination, epidemics that are useful for epidemiological or infection control, outbreaks in an institution (such as hospitals and schools) , bioterrorism-related outbreaks, outbreaks among susceptible populations, epidemics causing public alarm, epidemics of large scale or rapidly spreading proportions, etc. , these are listed by the respiratory disease as areas for further investigation or emergency response.

Suspected cases of respiratory disease, plague, SARS, Middle East Respiratory Syndrome and Hantavirus Lung Syndrome that require immediate public health intervention can be identified by health officials to assess whether they should be defined as a potential outbreak. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention requires people to notify health officials at the city, county, or state level as soon as they find out, and to notify the centers through an Urdo e-mail or an emergency phone call.

Public Health Information needs to be translated into timely and effective decision-making when dealing with epidemics. Zhong Nanshan, a senior expert at the Chinese National Health and Human Health Commission, said the CDC had confirmed human-to-human transmission of COVID-19 in late December 2019, but had not released it because the CDC could only report it, that's for the local government to decide.

Feng Daxuan believes that the outbreak, if the bottom-up rapid disclosure, control is relatively easy, if all the top nod, it is slow.

The tragedy ends at the first line of Defense

A legendary figure in the battle of yellow fever in Philadelphia, Benjamin Rush was a philosopher, writer, politician, and dedicated social reformer, but he was also one of the most famous physicians of the 18th century in America. He chose to stay in the city and become the leader of the yellow fever war in Philadelphia.

The classic narrative of Dr. Râches's saga is that in the event of an epidemic, the primary health care system and its myriad staff are an important first line of defense, whether it's the 2009 H1N1 flu, the 2014 Zaire Ebolavirus, or the 2016 Zika outbreak, Shao concludes, in the midst of an epidemic, whether the primary health care system is perfect or not and the role of general practitioners are the key factors to determine the trend of the epidemic.

During the outbreak of the disease in Wuhan, one of the difficulties was the high pressure of fever outpatient service and the high risk of home isolation. Similarly, when Zaire ebolavirus spread from a small village in Guinea to other countries in West Africa, only Médecins Sans Frontières monitored communities, raising awareness and protecting patients, but they were overwhelmed and unable to sustain themselves. "action has been slow, sporadic and dangerously short of expectations, " they said in a briefing. "cooperation from others is urgently needed to control the disease. " MSF has proposed a solution: Allowing community GPS to play a more active role in reducing the spread of disease -- as a family doctor looking at the disease as a whole -- could contribute to the improvement of primary health care systems and conditions in Africa and elsewhere, help decision makers and other professionals understand the community.

When the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control War officially started, the community was the end of this war. The problem for the community, Xinhua reported, was that residents said they were not acting and shirking their responsibilities. There were also cases of insubordination of measures such as centralized isolation and admission to hospital after the patient was diagnosed with NCP. Shao pointed out that a lack of trust between the community and the government health care system could exacerbate the spread of the epidemic, in part because people may not follow the advice of public health authorities well enough to increase the risk of infection or transmission.

During the Ebola outbreak in west Africa, outbreaks often occurred in isolated communities due to poor transportation, bad weather, mistrust of aid workers, and fear of epidemics by government or international health officials, it has also become an important reason why the epidemic is so difficult to extinguish.

But even in settings like West Africa, which lack access to basic health services, there are ways to bridge the gap -- through the help of local community health workers and primary health care systems, use their shared background, culture and geographical proximity to overcome barriers of geography and trust to track infected patients and identify suspicious cases of exposure. Community Health Workers Increase Trust between the community and the government. The presence and establishment of such professionals and primary health-care networks has greatly enhanced the capacity for outbreak control, and their work has also eased the pressure on the number of hospital outpatients and enabled the effective prevention and control of the epidemic.

Feng's daughter, a pediatric emergency medicine specialist at Southwest Medical Center in the United States, is highly trained in everything from medical diagnostics to big data and technology. Unlike the SARS epidemic of 2003, where big data and artificial intelligence play an important role, China lacks both the emergency physician and the full range of training, Feng said.

In the United States, doctors'first line of defense is also when they detect a specific disease that has a significant public health impact, and they notify the local public health authorities of the low threshold. Public health departments in these states are scattered across the country, with the CDC coordinating information at the highest level. More importantly, the public health sector is "interconnected" with each other, making infectious disease reporting systems Operability.

In the hospital system, reports are usually handled by infectious disease specialists who are informed of specific positive cases of infectious disease, while reports are issued by microbiological laboratories or similar specialists. Reporting Infectious Diseases is considered a professional responsibility. In turn, practitioners are able to keep abreast of the prevalence of various reported diseases in the community. These updates often come with clinical information, allowing them to detect problems early and more effectively.

Find the weak signal

While the United States is well prepared to deal with the COVID-19, senior health and safety experts in the United States warn that vulnerabilities will eventually come to light. One problem is that many hospitals in the United States do not have many extra beds and may be constrained by supply chains. Hospitals also lack the ability to diagnose the virus.

Management scholar Karl Weick, whose research has become a classic in organizational management, points out that wildfires can not be extinguished because all prior preparation may be ineffective. Wildfires are merciless, often devouring everything in their path. VICKER's "weak signal" theory was adopted by Robert Hendler as one of the guiding principles of Hospital Management, and was used to train medical staff to look for initial inaccuracies and low visibility indicators of important events or trends, these so-called "weak signals" include infection control problems, potential medical errors, and personnel misconduct to be evaluated before a "weak signal" becomes a problem.

For example, the infusion pump problem is a "weak signal" example. Anyone who works in a hospital knows the risks to patients if the infusion pump is not accurate. One nurse noticed that the patient had deteriorated overnight due to underlying illness and was transferred to the ICU. She suspected that there might be a problem with the infusion pump the night before, she said, although she could not be sure, she reported the "weak signal. ". The pump was examined after nurses reported a "weak signal" and it was later found that the pumps and other pumps in use had conflicting information about the dosage of the drug, leading to an overdose in several patients. So the hospital immediately on all infusion pumps for careful inspection, and quarterly review of the report.

The ideal time for nurses to spot "weak signals" and report them is rare in the U. S. medical system, and in fact, people are reluctant to report them. Robert Hendler says this involves a culture of security and reporting in different countries and organizations. Hospitals and government departments alike are not accustomed to using "bad news" to correct problems. Instead, they simply do nothing: either minimize or suppress bad news. They are either worried about being blamed for it, or worried about negative media coverage, or worried about a loss in the share price.

At Parkland, Hendler was chief quality and safety officer, as a hospital in a period of transition from quality and safety to almost being closed by the government. To improve the safety culture in hospitals, Hendler said that if concerns about reporting by medical staff were not addressed, there would be "identification, notification and escalation" : After a weak signal is detected, it is important to ensure that there is a system in place to take action, encourage leaders to develop action plans based on findings. In addition to the complex and more in-depth investigation and assessment required, Parkland Hospital's safety report response is required within 7 days. Failure to report a problem is considered an employment violation and, depending on the severity of the medical problem, can result in dismissal.

That series of reports helped Hendler return troubled hospitals to the top 10 percent of hospitals in the United States over a three year period. In Shao's introduction, public hospitals in the United States may receive thousands of reports a month from medical personnel, compared with perhaps a few hundred a year in China. Parkland had 1,800 safety reports a month before Hendler left.

Jake Endy, a professor of medicine and Assistant Dean for Senior Medical Practice at the University of Pennsylvania's Perelman School of medicine, points out that the reporting system is not without conflicts of interest. If a hospital reports a specific high rate of infection, it could lead to major interventions or even the closure of the hospital. But it turns out that American health care professionals tend to do the right thing for patient safety, not the reputation of a particular institution.

So, Endy says, if there's a medical error, it's a system error, not the fault of a particular professional.

"American hospitals are trying to create a safety culture that is in the true sense 'error free' , " Robert Hendler told CAIJING.

The writer is a special correspondent for CAIJING. This article originally appeared in Caijing magazine on March 2,2020
